<TEXT>
a bomb thursday destroyed a bus full of 
police officers in medellin killing at least five policemen and 
injuring 15 authorities said 
the radio station rcn without identifying its sources said 66 
pounds of dynamite exploded beneath the bus as it crossed a street 
in the bello horizonte suburb of medellin hub for the major drug 
cartel in colombia the report said the bus which struck a taxi 
after the bomb went off was reduced to rubble 
police said the bus was carrying police officers to various 
sites of the city to help in the governments war against drug 
traffickers police and official sources said five were killed 
instantly and that most of the injured were in serious condition at 
local clinics 
the mayor of medellin juan gomez martinez said earlier 
thursday that he opposed a government dialogue with drug 
traffickers which some hope will restore peace to the country 
since midaugust there have been 225 bombings and bomb attempts 
leaving 31 dead and 218 injured 
the latest injury was late thursday when a bomb tossed from a 
passing car went off at the central telephone exchange in southern 
bogota injuring one person police said 
earlier thursday unidentified assailants in a taxi opened fire 
and killed two police officers assigned to guard the ecuadoran 
consulate in medellin authorities said 
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for either 
incident but a series of bombings and assassinations that have 
swept this country since the government declared war on traffickers 
nearly 10 weeks ago have been blamed on hitmen hired by the drug 
barons 
the attacks came a day after the country suffered its worst 
rebel violence in two years with guerrillas storming two 
northeastern towns and slaying at least six people according to 
army reports 
the army blamed wednesdays attacks on the national liberation 
army a shadowy procuban organization 
there were no known links between the attacks wednesday and 
thursday and the governments war with drug traffickers however 
the army has claimed for years without producing proof that some 
leftist guerrillas and drug traffickers work in tandem 
in the attack on the guards in medellin assailants traveling in 
a taxi opened fire on the police in front of the consulate 
downtown a medellin police spokesman told the associated press by 
telephone 
one guard was immediately killed while the other died later at a 
nearby clinic the spokesman said 
the spokesman said authorities were investigating whether the 
killings were carried out by terrorists 
the national radio network caracol quoted witnesses as saying 
the two guards were attacked when they went to the aid of another 
policeman attempting to make an arrest 
medellin a city of 2 million residents is the most wellknown 
city of those making up colombias cartels others include cartels 
in cali on the north coast of colombia and in bogota 
the government pressed ahead with the drug war wednesday 
notifying an purported member of the medellin cocaine cartel he was 
being extradited to the united states 
according to tv hoy the government told jose rafael abello 
silva 34 that he would be extradited 
police have said abello is the fourth most important figure in 
the cartel in charge of its activities on colombias atlantic 
coast 
abello also known by his nickname the monkey was arrested 
oct 10 in bogota and faces a charge by an oklahoma federal court 
of conspiracy to distribute cocaine 
under president virgilio barcos extradition decree abello has 
five days to appeal the extradition 
the government has extradited four suspected drug traffickers to 
the united states since it launched its crackdown on aug 19 after 
the assassination of opposition presidential candidate sen luis 
carlos galan 
suspected traffickers have responded to the crackdown with a 
series of bombings and assassinations 
in wednesdays rebel raids about 100 guerrillas invaded cachira 
and la vega towns in the state of norte de santander the armys 
2nd division reported 
the heaviest attack by about 60 men and women was in cachira 
a town of 15000 people about 250 miles northeast of bogota the 
guerrillas destroyed a police station with mortar shells and fired 
on police officers with automatic weapons 
two policemen were killed and seven injured during five hours of 
fighting an army communique said 
an hour after that assault began 40 rebels invaded la vega 15 
miles away and tried to overrun the police station there two 
policemen were wounded in the sevenhour battle the reports said 
one guerrilla died as the attackers fled the town of 5000 
people into the mountains the army communique said 
guerrillas also ambushed police sent in as reinforcements three 
officers died in an attack along a dirt road outside town 
the rebel attacks were the bloodiest since 1987 when more than 
50 people were killed during one month of fighting 
caracol said two other leftist groups the revolutionary armed 
forces of colombia and the peoples liberation army also 
participated in wednesdays attacks the army could not confirm the 
report 
</TEXT>
