<TEXT>
aftershocks usually happen within months 
after a main earthquake and on the same section of fault but they 
can occur a century later and on nearby faults an expert said 
wednesday 
earthquakes cluster into sequences by definition we call the 
biggest one the main shock any that happen before the biggest one 
are foreshocks and any that come after the biggest one are 
aftershocks said seismologist lucile jones of the us 
geological survey in pasadena 
by wednesday morning more than 4000 aftershocks rattled the 
same 30milelong section of the san andreas fault that caused the 
magnitude71 major earthquake that rocked the san francisco bay 
area on oct 17 according to the usgs in menlo park 
aftershocks generally become less powerful and less frequent 
over time the agency said 
based on statistical studies of past california quakes by jones 
and paul reasenberg the usgs on tuesday said that within two 
months there is about a 10 percent chance of a strong aftershock 
measuring 6 or larger on the richter scale 
during the same period there is a 45 percent chance of an 
aftershock of magnitude 50 or larger the agency said 
when a fault breaks to cause an earthquake there is a change in 
underground stress patterns resulting in aftershocks that tend to 
occur along the same segment of fault jones said but the stress 
changes mean aftershocks also can occur on the fault slightly 
beyond the segment that first broke or on other nearby faults 
she added 
aftershocks from a major quake like the oct 17 jolt could be 
over in a year or it could take 10 years she said 
and a great quake estimated at magnitude 8 rocked japan in 
1890 and we are still having aftershocks from that earthquake 
almost 100 years later jones said 
the quakes are considered aftershocks because there are still 
more earthquakes there than before that mainshock happened its 
still more than the background rate she explained 
aside from aftershocks quakes sometimes can trigger other 
quakes on adjacent segments of the same fault like zipper action 
up a fault she said 
in its tuesday statement the usgs said there is a very small 
but not zero chance that the oct 17 quake could be followed by 
an even larger jolt on the segment of the san andreas just north of 
the segment that already broke 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

