<TEXT>
there are still prophets of the hippie 
culture sprinkled in the santa cruz mountains and the 
quartercenturyold values of that communal counterculture have 
emerged from quake rubble 
this fertile region 60 miles south of san francisco was next to 
the epicenter of the oct 17 quake that rocked northern california 
killing dozens injuring thousands and causing damage that will 
exceed 71 billion 
many of the mountains around the city are inaccessible because 
of land and rockslides triggered by the quake but in the city 
limits there are signs of a revitalization of the dropout 
philosophy of the 1960s 
the prequake homeless population estimated at 1000 was 
joined oct 17 by hundreds displaced by the disaster 
on wednesday donations of food and clothing were being 
distributed to all comers and many quake refugees were still in 
shelters 
there is an awareness of self an intelligencia its not a me 
generation its a we generation said chris watkins who sells 
handmade leather goods 
people in santa cruz have always pulled together they are 
really in tune with each other it is the land time forgot 
watkins added 
like the counterculture of old there is a sizeable segment here 
who resent war racism poverty materialism and automation for 
the most part though malcontents have mellowed 
but the wacky image persists and not entirely without 
foundation meditative vegetarians resting on futon furniture 
soaking in hot tubs and tending organic herb gardens do exist 
health food stores proponents of new age religions 
merchandisers of healing crystals and even fivestar psychic 
susie stevens jarvis have a foothold here longhairs still drive 
tattered volkswagen buses through the streets 
there wasthe commune movement and the counterculture movement 
in the 60s and santa cruz was in the vanguard of this said 
local historian page smith who was a founding provost at the 
university of california santa cruz it is interesting to note the 
ucsc nickname is the banana slugs 
the counterculture was very evident when i came here from los 
angeles in 1964 the mountains were already sprinkled with 
prophets of the counterculture there certainly are more arts and 
crafts people per capita here than anywhere else in the country 
smith said 
the image of santa cruz as a flaky drugusing place was not 
too far off the mark smith said 
university regional historian randall jarrell said the communal 
life in the mountains of santa cruz has evolved considerably but 
adds there are certainly a few relics and remnants of the 
hippies a lot have matured and i would not say we are a hippie 
community as such 
i would say we are progressiveminded there is certainly an 
arts and crafts population but there arent that many candlemakers 
anymore 
ms jarrell said santa cruz has a history of communal living 
dating to the early 1900s when italians pooled money and resources 
in their wharf fishing endeavors 
this kind of communal coming together is deep in the culture 
here she said there is a basic feeling of tolerance here 
longtime resident joan ward said the hippie community in santa 
cruz has always represented only a small faction of the population 
the old rag for 25 years has always been old hippies strumming 
guitars and that sort of thing that is totally wrong we are 
wonderfully diverse ms ward said 
the diversity is obvious after all the seaside city of 45000 
recently held a ninth annual brussels sprout festival on its famous 
boardwalk there was sprouttossing sproutcutting and 
sproutcooking the annual cold water surf classic is next on the 
social agenda 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the peace accord worked out by in taif 
saudi arabia is the most serious arab attempt to end lebanons 14 
years of sectarian civil war but making it work is another matter 
lebanese legislators and arab league mediators who met in the 
saudi resort for three weeks achieved what was unthinkable a few 
weeks ago in a country that has had rival christian and moslem 
governments since september 1988 
the plan is the first to provide a framework for political 
reforms designed to share power equally between the traditionally 
dominant christians and moslems now an estimated 55 percent of 
lebanons 4 million people 
it is a fragile structure however because it does not resolve 
the political frustrations of militia leaders on both sides who 
were not represented at taif the accord also lacks a concrete plan 
for withdrawal of syrias 40000 soldiers stationed in lebanon 
which christians demand 
vagueness about withdrawal clearly leaves syria with a role in 
lebanon where it is the main power broker the agreement notes 
somewhat disingenuously given syrian control of 70 percent of the 
country that syria will not permit any act that threatens 
lebanons security independence or sovereignty 
arab and foreign pressure may force militia leaders to accept 
the accord which lebanons warweary people hope will end a war 
that taken more than 150000 lives and displaced onefourth of the 
population but there are many pitfalls 
deeply embedded distrust on both sides and rivalries of syria 
israel iraq iran and libya played out in lebanon could wreck the 
plan as they did peace efforts in 1983 1984 and 1985 
reaching agreement in taif is likely to be childs play in 
comparison to putting that agreement into effect in lebanon 
analyst charles snow wrote in the respected middle east economic 
survey 
the taif accord reduces the dominant role of maronite catholics 
the main christian sect in the government and parliament and gives 
moslems more power than they have had since independence from 
france in 1943 
it envisages a government of national reconcilitiation that will 
restore central authority and election of a president acceptable to 
all sides 
nabih berri leader of the shiite moslem militia amal says the 
agreement does not give the 12 million shiites the largest sect 
in lebanon a share of power commensurate with their numbers 
walid jumblatt the druse moslem chieftain voiced grudging 
acceptance to support his syrian allies but clearly is far from 
happy with it the druse a mystical offshoot of islam long hostile 
to the christians form only 6 percent of the population and fear 
for their survival 
for maronites led the army commander gen michel aoun the 
major flaw in the agreement is its failure to be specific about 
syrian withdrawal 
aoun considers syria an occupying power ironically the syrians 
moved into lebanon in april 1976 to help save the christians from 
being overwhelmed by an alliance of leftists moslems and 
palestinians 
syria feared the leftists and palestinians would control a 
radical state on its vulnerable western flank and precipitate an 
israeli invasion which came to pass in 1982 
later in 1976 the arab league conferred some legality on the 
syrian action by giving it a peacekeeping mandate 
in the kaledeiscope of changing alliances in lebanon the 
syrians soon found themselves fighting the christians aoun says 
syria has violated the arab league mandate by openly siding with 
the moslems 
in march he began a war of liberation against the syrians 
that involved some of the most ferocious artillery battles of the 
war more than 900 people were killed and nearly 3000 wounded 
nearly all of them civilians 
outgunned and outnumbered he gambled that outside powers would 
compel syria to withdraw but western powers were wary of the 
lebanese quagmire and stayed aloof aoun was left isolated with 
little choice but to accept an arab league ceasefire on sept 22 
george saadeh leader of the rightwing phalange party and 
other maronite legislators defied aouns demand that they refuse 
concessions at taif until they had guarantees of syrian withdrawal 
aoun sees himself as a national savior a man with a 
mission a lebanese analyst said privately that makes him 
dangerous hes taking on everyone in sight but he cant stand 
alone against the whole arab world and the international 
community 
samir geagea leader of the main christian militia and maronite 
patriarch nasrallah sfeir have endorsed the taif agreement causing 
speculation about aouns continued control of the christian 
government and army 
syria as in the past has linked its departure to israeli 
withdrawal from the security zone it maintains just inside 
south lebanon israel cites the presence of guerrillas in the area 
as a security threat and shows no signs of leaving 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ed blanche is middle east news editor of the 
associated press formerly based in beirut and now in nicosia 
</TEXT>
