<TEXT>
farmers who planted crops to replace those 
damaged or destroyed by drought this year would get increased 
federal disaster aid under legislation approved by the senate 
the bill represents a boon to farmers who say agriculture 
department restrictions are too stringent and fail to take into 
account the expense involved in producing replacement crops this 
year 
it goes to the house after winning senate approval on a voice 
vote wednesday 
the agriculture department imposed the restrictions with an eye 
to preventing farmers from collecting disaster payments for crop 
damage and then keeping the entire amount while producing a new 
crop on the same acreage in the same growing season 
the idea is that the disaster payments are designed to offset 
losses and should not go to farmers whose losses were reduced or 
even erased through production of a second crop 
but the senate has been more sympathetic to growers who say the 
departments restrictions were unrealistically tightfisted 
this should more accurately reflect the expenses and income of 
the farmer sen lloyd bentsen dtexas said in a statement 
in addition it will protect the many farmers who are making 
little if any profit on that second crop from losing the disaster 
payments which they were expecting on the first crop 
the bill earlier was one of many provisions for special 
interests included in a major deficitreduction measure but it 
became a casualty when lawmakers removed all such features from the 
deficit reduction plan 
the agriculture department has been planning to deduct 75 
percent of the gross value of any replacement crop from such a 
farmers disaster aid check 
the bill would modify the system considerably 
in figuring the value of the replacement crop the department 
would first deduct 50 percent of the county average yield for the 
second crop 
the initial plan would require even farmers who had replanted 
only a few acres to wait until harvesting their second crop before 
obtaining disaster benefits for damage to the first crop 
that would be canceled under the legislation 
meanwhile the senate also approved on a voice vote and sent to 
the house a bill that would allow the agriculture department to 
allow oat producers to plant their entire base acreage and still 
remain in the farm program 
the department requires them as a condition of being in the 
program to refrain from planting on a portion of the historical 
acreage base they use for oats 
the provision was contained in a bill with features designed to 
aid an array of farm interests 
the measure also would earmark 14 million this fiscal year 
93 million next year and 46 million the year after to boost 
us beef exports the payments would be in cash or commodities 
under the export enhancement program a major sources of subsidies 
to stimulate overseas shipments over the last five years 
the measure also contained technical changes in programs 
operated by the department for egg producers peanut growers and 
research into new commercial products derived from plant materials 
