president bushs unwillingness to take a 
strong lead in developing a us highdefinition television 
industry is hurting americas ability to compete overseas hdtv 
proponents say 
more than 100 business leaders members of congress and 
technical experts wrote to bush on wednesday to say they were 
deeply disturbed that the united states is failing to match 
japanese and european efforts on hdtv according to the 
congressional hdtv caucus 
the caucus said that among those signing the letter were john 
mitchell chairman of motorola corp robert noyce head of the 
sematech computerchip consortium jerry pearlman chief executive 
officer of zenith corp which has proposed a us hdtv 
transmission system and mitchell kertzman chairman of the 
american electronics association which has urged the government to 
commit 135 billion in matching funds over five years to spur hdtv 
development 
more than 25 members of congress signed the letter the caucus 
said 
hdtv proponents say the new technology which promises motion 
picturesharp images and compact discquality sound could be the 
technology driver that could revitalize the us electronics 
industry and have important applications in medicine defense and 
other industries 
but a congressional budget office report in august said hdtv 
claims were very optimistic and that even under the rosiest of 
scenarios hdtv sales will be small relative to other electronic 
equipment markets 
the house has appropriated 50 million development money for 
next year and the defense advanced projects agency is providing 
30 million in seed money for defenserelated hdtv equipment 
but the bush administration otherwise has shown little 
inclination to push hdtv development 
rep mel levine dcalif cochair of the caucus said 
wednesday that the bush administrations unwillingness to take a 
strong lead on hdtv seriously handicaps this nations ability to 
compete internationally 
while the japanese and europeans outpace our technology 
efforts daily the administration sits on the sidelines waiting for 
an economic miracle to revitalize our industrial base he said 
we need an hdtv initiative today not promises of a broader 
technology program tomorrow 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher told congress earlier this 
year that developing a policy on hdtv was among the 
administrations highest priorities although the government didnt 
plan to play uncle sugar to american industry 
but commerce officials last month said that outlook had changed 
and the administration now was looking at hdtv only as part of a 
broadbased effort to boost us technological competitiveness 
