<TEXT>
most american homes have smoke detectors but 
as many as half of them are useless because the batteries are old 
missing or have been ripped out by residents who cant stand the 
noise fire officials say 
the number of homes in the united states that have detectors has 
increased during the last decade from 22 percent to 80 percent 
the problem is we also estimate that probably as much as 
50 percent of those detectors dont work said jim estepp 
president of the international association of fire chiefs 
sometimes it gets very discouraging we have the worst fire 
loss record of any country in the industrialized world 
the organization is pushing a national fire safety awareness 
campaign called change your clock change your battery asking 
people to make a habit of changing smoke detector batteries when 
they change clocks from daylightsaving time each year 
daylightsaving time ends at 2 am sunday 
the simple act of changing the batteries in smoke detectors is 
the single most easy and accessible way of making a difference in 
the number of deaths and injuries caused by fire said estepp 
who is also chief of the prince georges county md fire 
department 
about 1500 departments across the country will join in the 
batterychanging campaign this weekend 
according to figures compiled by the organization more than 
500000 residential fires occur in the united states each year 
killing nearly 6000 people and causing serious injuries for 
130000 
estepp said the number of firerelated deaths went down as smoke 
detectors took hold in the united states in the early 1980s but in 
recent years the number of deaths leveled off and actually 
increased in 1988 
fire officials attribute the trend in large part to smoke alarm 
neglect 
estepp recalled a house fire in his own jurisdiction this year 
in which a 16yearold boy died in a fire that started when his 
twin brother fell asleep after putting grease on the stove to cook 
french fries 
they had taken the smoke detectors down to replace the 
batteries and never put them back up estepp said you can 
repeat that scenario just about every day 
this week after a st louis woman and her son died in a house 
fire relatives told authorities she had disconnected the smoke 
alarm because of the chirping noise it made as the batteries wore 
down 
