un poll watcher elliot richardson says 
nicaragua is headed for a free fair and honest election 
despite the state departments stated fear that the leftist 
sandinista government will rig the vote 
richardson a former us attorney general is secretarygeneral 
javier perez de cuellars personal representative for monitoring 
the campaign for nicaraguas feb 25 presidential and national 
assembly elections 
he briefed reporters wednesday before reporting to perez de 
cuellar on his weekend talks in nicaragua with president daniel 
ortega and members of the supreme electoral council which 
interprets the election laws 
the council has been performing in a conscientious fair and 
impartial manner richardson said 
it is certainly my impression and i think that i speak for 
all of us representing the united nations in nicaragua that the 
goal of a free fair and honest election is being taken seriously 
by all those concerned in the government in the parties and 
among the people he said 
on monday us ambassador thomas r pickering said the state 
department fears the ruling sandinistas are trying to rig 
nicaraguas election and cited the reported presence of armed 
soldiers at nicaraguan voter registration centers 
richardsons un team had observers at many polling places 
during the four sundays in october on which voters registered and 
he said i cannot tell you that they did not see any soldiers or 
guards 
however he said no one complained to him about intimidation 
this is not a matter that has been brought to my attention 
the sandinista government reported several attacks on polling 
places over the weekend that it blamed on usbacked contra rebels 
it accused the rebels to whom washington now provides only 
nonlethal aid of trying to disrupt the voting process 
richardson served as attorney general under president richard 
nixon and is remembered for his refusal to fire watergate special 
prosecutor archibald cox on the orders of the white house on oct 
10 1973 
he resigned rather than carry out the order 
