<TEXT>
a tablet on a plain narrow cross tucked 
away almost hidden in a corner of a cemetery on warsaws southern 
outskirts bears chilling witness to polands torment during the 
stalinist years 
in mokotowski prison there was a shot in the back of the 
head and then a little horse brought us to sluzew 
the unsigned verse and cross in walbrzyska street cemetery mark 
where an estimated 500 to 3000 political prisoners were buried 
after being executed or tortured to death at mokotowski prison 
during the late 1940s and early 1950s 
the prison is about three miles away from the sluzew burial 
ground 
on a golden autumn day children play and men wash cars only a 
few steps away from the cross in a parking lot where some of the 
victims are thought to lie drab modern housing blocks stretch 
along a small adjacent stream 
only a few curious visitors find their way to the cross to lay 
a flower or say a prayer 
but now four decades later people are beginning to talk openly 
about the midnight burials 40 years ago when sluzew then a tiny 
hamlet seemed a safe place to hide a shameful deed 
and for the first time saturday the still unidentified victims 
will have a funeral mass said for them at nearby st catherines 
church 
the parish priest the rev jozef maj is leading the struggle 
to lay bare the history of the executions and help families whose 
loved ones may lie here 
the victims were from the leading circles of poland the ones 
who might have created centers of social support who might have 
formed an alternative leadership he says of those killed by the 
kremlinimposed communist regime as it waged class war and 
consolidated power in poland after world war ii 
if the new solidarityled coalition government led by prime 
minister tadeusz mazowiecki is to establish its credibility the 
priest said it can start by helping to find out the truth about 
the killings 
indeed the mazowiecki government has shown great interest in 
examining the dark postwar years in poland when the political 
persecution stalin practiced at home also found favor among the men 
ruling eastern european countries under soviet influence 
justice minister aleksander bentkowski this month issued an 
appeal for evidence of stalinistera crimes for his ministry to 
investigate 
a longbanned movie about the period the interrogation is 
now being released in stateowned cinemas and state television 
news this week broadcast majs story of the walbrzyska street 
cemetery 
the cemetery stands as a symbol of the martyrdom of poles 
during the communist terror says malgorzata shejnert of the 
churchsocial committee for homage to the victims of the terror of 
the authorities in the years 194556 
it also symbolizes the indestructability of memory 
the memory of the burials was kept alive by a few older 
residents of the area 
they say victims were brought by night in horsedrawn wagons and 
buried just outside the new cemetery of st catherines on 
walbrzyska street maj said most of the burials took place between 
1945 abnd 1951 but he has heard of one as late as autumn 1956 
according to the local accounts lime was poured on the bodies 
and the ground was afterward leveled 
after two years there was no sign of a grave of a body or 
bones that was the point of this method maj said 
further evidence of the burials came last year when st 
catherines one of the areas oldest churches was cleaning out 
its archives preparing for its 750th anniversary as a parish next 
year 
the archive keeper found letters from majs predecessor canon 
adam wyrebowski who had written to both the ministry of public 
security and the rakowiecka street prison about the burials in 
unhallowed ground 
still more proof comes from poetry such as the verse on the 
narrow cross in sluzew that circulated among prisoners at 
mokotowski prison 
maj says it is believed bodies were buried in what is now the 
back section of the churchs cemetery expanded in 1959 in a 
meadow leading down to the stream where the apartment blocks now 
stand and around the city horserace track a few miles away 
already people are coming to me bringing their reports and 
whatever different documents they possess he said 
maj said he has also heard of such burial sites in rawicz and 
wroclaw provinces and there may be others 
maybe the number of victims and some of their names will be 
established said mrs szejnert said on state tv but even then 
the families will not find any remains and the place where the 
relatives rest will only be known inexactly 
</TEXT>
