<TEXT>
the federal government will allow wider 
distribution to children of azt the only governmentapproved 
antiaids drug health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
announced today 
the action marks the first time any aids drug has been approved 
even conditionally for use in children under 13 
the drug will be available under what the food and drug 
administration calls a treatment ind which allows widespread 
distribution of a drug that appears to be promising on the basis of 
clinical trials 
todays action is a significant advance in extending aids 
therapy to children it will give many sick children availability 
to a drug that offers promise for improving or even extending their 
lives sullivan said in a statement announcing the program 
we still need more data to be absolutely sure about the full 
range of effects from azt sullivan said on abctvs good 
morning america program but we have enough preliminary 
evidence that the drug is effective and seems to be safe under the 
conditions of usage 
sullivan said studies on azt in children will continue 
this is indeed an interim process before the drug is finally 
approved for use in children the secretary said 
in the past many physicians have been reluctant to use azt 
for children because it is not labeled for this use and because of 
concerns that the drugs side effects might be even more severe in 
children sullivan said in a speech to an aids conference but 
clinical data now indicates that children receiving azt experience 
the same degree of side effects that occur in adults 
children ages 3 months to 12 years who have symptoms of advanced 
infection with the aids virus will be eligible to receive it free 
under the program sponsored by the maker of azt burroughs wellcome 
co based in research triangle park nc 
according to the latest count by the national centers for 
disease control in atlanta 1859 children under 13 have aids they 
constitute about 2 percent of all aids cases 
mathilde krim of the american foundation for aids research said 
the announcement was a good step but was overdue 
sullivan defended against such criticism saying we really 
have a very careful balancing act that we have to undertake first 
of all we want to be sure that the drugs we approve are effective 
for what they are intended to do but at the same time we need to 
be sure that they do not have adverse side effects that might 
override the beneficial effects of the drug 
krim also said she is worried about future access to the drug 
what worries me is once this is marketed how available will 
it be to children when it is no longer distributed free she said 
she said 75 percent of children with aids are from poor and 
modestincome families often minorities where the mother and 
father also have aids but may not qualify for medicaid they 
wont have the means to buy the treatment for themselves or their 
kids she said a years course of azt now costs between 2700 
and 6500 depending on the dose 
azt is now available in the form of a new strawberryflavored 
syrup that is easier for children to swallow than capsules are it 
also allows dosages to be adjusted for body size 
zidovudine commonly called azt and which attacks the aids 
virus was approved by the food and drug administration for 
teenagers and adults with advanced symptoms of aids in march 1987 
recently completed studies have shown the drug extends the lives 
of adults with aids and delays the development of symptoms in those 
who are infected with the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv but 
are not yet sick 
though the drug is not labeled for use in children physicians 
still could prescribe it for this age group however many have 
been reluctant because of fears that the side effects of the highly 
toxic drug may be more severe in children than in adults the 
sources said 
but research studies that involved more than 200 children have 
indicated that azt may prolong their survival without raising the 
risk of side effects 
it seems the drug is as effective in kids as in adults and the 
toxicity risks are about the same one source said 
in september researchers reported that the most extensive study 
of azt in children part of a national institutes of health 
project showed the drug is safe helps children gain weight and 
avoid lifethreatening infections and improves their wellbeing 
studies will continue to evaluate the effects on children of azt 
in combination with other drugs and the benefits of the drug when 
used in children in earlier stages of the disease 
physicians who want to enroll child patients in the azt program 
can call burroughs wellcomes tollfree number 18008297337 from 
8 am to 7 pm edt 
</TEXT>
