<TEXT>
the chilly climate of tibet has been warmer 
over the past halfcentury than at any time in thousands of years 
a team of scientists sponsored by the national science foundation 
reported thursday 
the analysis of ice collected in remote northcentral tibet 
revealed what the scientists termed a striking warming in that 
region since the 1940s 
their report in the journal science is based on the different 
types of oxygen that collect in ice at different temperatures it 
does not include estimates of actual temperature changes in tibet 
the study was conducted by researchers from the byrd polar 
research center at ohio state university the chinese institute of 
glaciology and geocryology and the university of copenhagen 
denmark 
they compared the various isotopes of oxygen in accumulated ice 
to analyse temperature changes in tibet over the past 6000 to 
8000 years and concluded that the readings suggest recent 
temperatures are the warmest 
a connection with any greenhouse effect global warming has 
not been established the researchers said 
the term greenhouse warming refers to a possibility of 
rising temperatures worldwide that has many researchers concerned 
about disruptive changes in world climate 
another report on that topic appeared thursday in the british 
journal nature where researchers concluded that the worlds oceans 
and seas did not show significant warming from 1982 to mid1988 
contradicting earlier reports 
the reports of warming in tibet but none in the oceans could be 
consistent with one another however 
james e hansen of the national aeronautics and space 
administration a leading spokesman on the global warming issue 
has estimated that if greenhouse warming is taking place the large 
land masses would be affected sooner and more strongly than the 
oceans 
thus an area such as tibet landlocked in the largest 
continent could be expected to record a warming before any of the 
worlds oceans which absorb heat and change temperature much more 
slowly than does the land 
the greenhouse warming according to scientists could result 
from the gradual increase in carbon dioxide in the atmosphere due 
to industrial processes the fear is that this gas would trap heat 
somewhat like a greenhouse causing temperatures to rise 
however other scientists question this theory and urge more 
research before taking any actions to halt the threatened climate 
change 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

