<TEXT>
the un high commissioner for refugees 
jeanpierre hocke resigned today amid an investigation focusing on 
his use of un money for firstclass air travel 
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar accepted hockes 
resignation effective nov 1 said un spokesman francois giuliani 
hocke a swiss was in new york as his resignation was 
announced his letter to perez de cuellar read by giuliani said 
in part 
at a time when you have decided to prolong and intensify 
an investigation which you initiated i do not wish my presence at 
the head of hcr to complicate in any way the ongoing 
investigation 
the high commissioner serves a three year term hocke won the 
post in 1986 as the favored candidate of the us state department 
and won reinstatement in january 
the commissioner is officially responsible for at least 12 
million refugees worldwide though there are many more than that 
hockes fouryear tenure was plagued by allegations of 
mismanagement and favoritism to the major donor nations which 
include the united states 
his latest problem erupted in september when swiss television 
reported he used a special educational fund set up by sweden 
and denmark to upgrade his air travel to firstclass 
hocke admitted he had flown firstclass a right reserved only 
for perez de cuellar under stringent un austerity measures but 
he denied impropriety 
the commission is struggling with a shortfall of at least 40 
million in its budget this year 
the swiss television report said internal documents showed hocke 
had drawn 300000 dollars since 1987 from the special 
educational account to upgrade his flights from business to 
firstclass 
hocke said in late september that he had flown firstclass on 
some long intercontinental flights when he had a busy work schedule 
the fund was established in the late 1960s and is replenished 
by sweden and denmark 
on tuesday danish foreign minister uffe ellemannjensen said 
that hocke told officials that the unhcrs fundraising director 
ole volfing told him danish authorities had approved the fund for 
travel costs 
in recent years hocke has been criticized by his staff and 
private refugee relief groups for not challenging the increasingly 
restrictive asylum policies of the united states west germany and 
other major donors to the refugee commission 
in january 1988 hocke ordered the burning of all 138000 copies 
of the agencys official monthly magazine refugees because it 
contained an article critical of west germanys refugee policy 
hocke said the article was out of date and west germanys 
policies were improving but the book burning image engendered 
by the move greatly embarrassed bonn 
</TEXT>
