the roman catholic church entered the 
world of polish primetime television thursday with the first 
broadcast of a regular weekly religious show believed to be the 
first such program in eastern europe 
the church which claims more than 90 percent of poles as 
believers has long sought access to television 
but while coverage of such major religious events as papal 
visits to poland and polishborn pope john paul iis christmas mass 
had been permitted in recent years the former communist rulers 
long balked at allowing regular religious programming 
finally in connection with a new law establishing the legal 
basis for the churchs activities in poland an agreement allowing 
the church television and radio programs was concluded in june with 
the previous communist government 
the rev andrzej koprowski the host of the new show said 
before the broadcast that it answers the needs of the 
overwhelmingly catholic society which had listed a demand for 
broadcast masses in the labor upheaval that gave rise to solidarity 
in august 1980 
