<TEXT>
president bush extended mostfavorednation 
trade status to hungary on thursday ending 15 years of us 
economic sanctions 
bushs action at a rose garden ceremony made hungary the first 
nation to be freed from trade restrictions imposed under the 
socalled jacksonvanik amendment which links human rights to 
trade policy 
the sanctions have been the centerpiece of us trade policy 
toward the communist world and remain largely in place against the 
soviet union and most nations in eastern europe 
but bush praised hungary which declared itself a democracy 
three days ago for riding at the crest of the historic tide 
of freedom sweeping eastern europe 
hungary fulfilled its part of the bargain and im here to 
fulfill our part of the bargain bush said 
he noted that he had promised hungary such trade treatment 
during his trip to budapest in july if the hungarian government 
took steps to liberalize its emigration policy 
the action gives hungary full access to us markets and the 
lowest possible tariff rates putting it on an equal footing with 
major us trading partners 
the jacksonvanik amendment to the trade act of 1974 denies 
trade benefits to nations that restrict emigration it is named 
after its congressional sponsors the late sen henry m jackson 
dwash and former rep charles vanik rohio 
bush said that hungary under legislation approved by its 
parliament on sept 26 now meets all the freeemigration 
requirements of us law 
todays action signals the recognition that a quiet 
revolution is taking place in thousands of shops and farms and 
factories bush said at a ceremony signing documents exempting 
hungary from the jacksonvanik sanctions it signals the rebirth 
of hungary as an entrepreneurial nation 
the people of america are exchanging more than blue jeans and 
fine wines were exchanging ideas and ideals that can only be the 
shared province of free people he added 
the jacksonvanik law requires an annual report to congress on 
the emigration policies of each nation covered under the 
restriction and an assessment of whether there has been progress 
toward unrestricted emigration 
bush signed a report to congress asserting that hungary does not 
deny its citizens the right or opportunity to emigrate 
there are no known cases of government refusal to allow 
emigration from hungary whether to join a close family member in 
the united states or for any other reason the report said 
on capitol hill meanwhile senate majority leader george 
mitchell said that us aid to poland and hungary will be delayed 
and perhaps killed by a republican attempt to inject capital gains 
tax reductions into the aid debate 
but republican leader bob dole accused democrats of injecting 
partisan politics into the debate over the size of the aid package 
and said republicans had no choice but to seek action on capital 
gains on every possible bill 
</TEXT>
