the weather turned against volunteers 
thursday as they resumed the search for a 9yearold boy missing 
with his pony for more than three days in rugged southcentral 
oregon 
as the search began again at daybreak heavy snow was falling 
and the temperature was 20 degrees said klamath county search and 
rescue spokeswoman betty lucht 
the snow continued through the morning as about 130 people 
looked for the boy about a third of them on horseback said 
sheriffs spokesman dexter patmon 
nathan madsen who lives in rural veneta disappeared sunday 
afternoon while herding cattle with his family during an annual 
roundup family members said the boy and his 10yearold sorrel 
tony were inseparable and would have stayed together 
the number of searchers thursday was down from a high of about 
350 the day before but patmon said that was not necessarily bad 
since more searchers might obscure signs of the boy and his horse 
confusing the situation 
lucht said a us forest service crew of smokejumpers brought in 
to search through the night determined that a set of hoofprints 
found wednesday did not belong to the missing boys pony klamath 
county sheriff carl burkhart had called the hoofprints the first 
good news since the search began but lucht said they turned out 
to be prints left by a searchers horse 
contingency plans were in place to airlift the child to a 
hospital in bend if he is found said maj pat kelly of the us 
air force reserves 304th aerospace rescue and recovery squadron 
the unit sent two helicopters and a military transport airplane to 
the area wednesday to help in the search 
the poor weather kept the helicopters grounded thursday morning 
however said sheriffs dispatcher becky collins 
the temperature was below freezing for the fourth straight 
night but the sheriff said authorities were optimistic about the 
boys chances 
the boy was dressed in a slicker and chaps and his mother 
sarah madsen said earlier that she was confident her son could 
take care of himself until he is found 
