<TEXT>
the government is settling a lawsuit filed by 
the widow of a communist party leader who was ostracized by his 
colleagues after the bureau planted a forged document falsely 
suggesting the man was an informant 
the 177000 settlement which will go to the widow of william 
albertson of new york city is the largest ever made in connection 
with abuses by the fbis cointelpro operation the american civil 
liberties union said thursday 
under cointelpro which stands for counterintelligence program 
the fbi used a variety of tactics to disrupt antiwar groups civil 
rights advocates and radical organizations in the united states 
the program ended in 1971 
albertson was a national committee member of the communist party 
in 1964 when the fbi created a phony report in which albertson 
appeared to be asking his fbi handler for more money according to 
internal bureau documents released as part of a lawsuit filed by 
albertsons wife lillie 
the fbi slipped the handwritten document signed bill into a 
car in which albertson rode to party meetings 
party members found the note confronted albertson didnt 
believe his denials that the document which appeared to be in his 
handwriting was forged and kicked him out of the party 
he was stripped of his job running a partyowned bookstore his 
wife and mother were expelled from the party and his children bore 
the stigma of having an informer for a father 
the fbi agents who set up the operation were recommended for 
incentive awards according to a july 7 1964 fbi headquarters memo 
released as part of the albertson case 
in a message to the field fbi director j edgar hoover said 
headquarters is extremely pleased with the sophisticated and 
imaginative counterintelligence action against albertson 
albertson spent the next eight years trying to clear his name 
with party officials and became increasingly depressed because he 
was having difficulty finding work his wife said 
it was really the destruction of a human being mrs 
albertson told a news conference at aclu offices its just not 
something the government should be doing 
he was committeed to socialism the community party the labor 
movement his mother said it would have been better had they killed 
him 
she said some of her husbands old party colleagues have told 
her recently that they never really believed he was an informer 
but she said some of those same people denounced him at the time 
the settlement ends a dispute over information the justice 
department says would endanger national security if it were 
publicly disclosed in the course of the lawsuit 
the department invoked the statesecret privilege to protect the 
information but a federal appeals court ruled 21 this year that 
albertson could proceed with the case 
in a dissent appeals court judge douglas ginsburg said the 
government had a legitimate and compelling interest in preventing 
disclosure of exceedingly senstive national security information 
disclosure of evidence would pose a serious risk to the 
personal safety of government informants assistant fbi director 
james geer said in an affidavit 
under the settlement the aclu agreed to move jointly with the 
government to vacate the appeals court opinion this would mean the 
apeallate court decision would not have any legal significance as a 
precedent 
as part of the settlement the justice department will withdraw 
a petition for supreme court review of the case 
both sides stipulated that the settlement was not an admission 
of liability or fault by the us government 
