the justice department charged thursday that a 
pittsburgh suburb is violating federal civil rights law by 
restricting the number of group homes for disabled people 
the departments civil rights division sought to join a private 
lawsuit against moon township pa by three mentally retarded 
persons who are trying to prevent their eviction from a group home 
the lawsuit challenges a township zoning ordinance stating that 
group homes cannot be located within a mile of one another a 
restriction the justice department contended discriminates against 
residents of such facilities 
moon township manager greg smith said the suburb has 14 or 15 
group homes and didnt object to others moving in but enacted the 
ordinance because township officials wanted the handicapped 
residents to have a normal neighborhood setting rather than be 
concentrated in a few areas 
the issue came to a head when four or five group homes opened in 
one apartment complex he said 
we didnt want to have one home after another in a row we 
wanted a normal situation smith said our basis was spread 
them out so that one neighborhood wouldnt be inundated 
the zoning code makes dwellings unavailable to persons on 
account of handicap in violation of the fair housing act the 
justice department said it sought an injunction to prevent the 
township from enforcing the provision 
the justice departments action marks the first time the federal 
government has sought under the newly amended fair housing act to 
set aside a zoning ordinance on the ground it is discriminatory 
said spokesman david runkel 
the fairhousing amendments which took effect last spring 
prohibit housing discrimination on the basis of a handicap the law 
allows the department to intervene in private discrimination 
lawsuits 
the justice department intends to use all of the new 
enforcement tools at our disposal under the amended fair housing 
act to redress housing discrimination james p turner acting 
head of the civil rights division said in a statement 
in june the department filed a suit charging that chicago 
heights ill had violated the fair housing act by denying a 
specialuse permit for the construction of a group home for 15 
mentally retarded adults that case is still pending in federal 
court in chicago 
