prime minister margaret thatchers treasury chief 
nigel lawson and her personal economic adviser both resigned 
thursday in a dramatic government upheaval during difficult 
economic times 
lawson quit his cabinet post as chancellor of the exchequer 
saying he could not work for mrs thatcher unless she dropped her 
adviser sir alan walters 
walters who was visiting the united states resigned shortly 
afterward 
mrs thatcher expressed the most profound regret after 
lawsons resignation but moved quickly to demonstrate stability by 
replacing him with her foreign secretary john major home 
secretary douglas hurd became foreign secretary 
no replacement was announced for walters and no other details 
on the shakeup were immediately available 
the financial markets were shaken by the news and the pound fell 
3 cents against the dollar 
lawson 57 had held the job since 1983 engineering tax cuts 
and an economic recovery that won him mrs thatchers praise as one 
of britains greatest chancellors 
it was the first time since the 1986 resignation of defense 
secretary michael heseltine that mrs thatcher has had a senior 
cabinet official quit on her 
lawson and thatcher appeared to be in close harmony as long as 
the economic boom lasted but when it began to falter 18 months 
ago reports of discord surfaced 
they were said to disagree over the pound with lawson 
advocating a managed exchange rate and mrs thatcher insisting it 
be controlled by market forces 
lawson also was thought to favor britain joining the european 
monetary system a mechanism for stabilizing exchange rates mrs 
thatcher favors joining only after britains inflation rate moves 
down and capital flows freely in europe 
walters bluntly opposed joining the ems and has criticized 
lawsons policies 
in his letter of resignation lawson wrote the successful 
conduct of economic policy is possible only if there is and is 
seen to be full agreement between the prime minister and the 
chancellor of the exchequer 
recent events have confirmed that this essential requirement 
cannot be satisfied so long as alan walters remains your personal 
economic adviser 
