<TEXT>
research scientists on thursday criticized the 
energy departments plans for greater competition for funds between 
two different approaches toward harnessing fusion the energy 
source of the sun and stars 
the researchers told a house panel they would like to see a 
substantial increase perhaps as much as a doubling of government 
support for both approaches magnetic fusion and inertial 
confinement fusion 
a billion dollars a year to me does not seem like too much to 
have an energy future said robert l mccrory director of the 
laboratory for laser energetics at the university of rochester 
for the current fiscal year that began oct 1 the department 
has about 510 million for fusion research 340 million for 
magnetic fusion and 170 for inertial confinement fusion 
fusion is the release of energy by the combination of certain 
forms of hydrogen atoms to make helium enormous amounts of energy 
are required to trigger the reaction 
the magnetic approach uses powerful magnetic fields to compress 
a superheated gas plasma whirling at high speed within a 
doughnutshaped apparatus known as a tokamak 
the inertial confinement approach would fire laser or particle 
beams at a peasized target to try to attain the extremely high 
temperatures and pressures needed 
in opening the hearing rep robert a roe dnj chairman of 
the house science investigations and oversight subcommittee said 
that fusion energy needs to be a central part of our energy 
policy for the next century 
we should take the lead in developing for the world a 
technology that will allow china to stop burning dirty coal that 
will remove the need for using the amazon forest as a fuel source 
and that will save our atmosphere from pollution and warming he 
said 
earlier this month robert o hunter director of the energy 
departments office of energy research testified the department 
favors a competition between magnetic and inertial confinement 
fusion with a winner to be selected early in the next century 
however mccrory said he was worried that such a competition 
could be used as a pretext for shortchanging the effort to achieve 
useful fusion energy 
erik storm deputy associate director for inertial confinement 
fusion at lawrence livermore national laboratory livermore 
calif said the two approaches to fusion should be complementary 
and collaborative rather than being in competition 
he predicted that very ambitious research and development 
probably could produce prototype fusion plants by 2020 but without 
substantial increases in spending it might take 30 to 50 years 
longer 
</TEXT>
