<TEXT>
incidents of shootings on los angeles county 
roads soared between 1985 and 1987 but contrary to popular 
belief most gunplay occurred on streets instead of highways 
researchers said thursday 
it was occurring on the surface streets and everyone thought 
it was the freeways so they were trying to avoid the freeways 
said chukwudi onwuachisaunders lead author of the study published 
in fridays journal of the american medical association 
in 45 percent of the cases drivers said there was no 
confrontation before the attack said the researchers from the 
national centers for disease control in atlanta 
there were 32 firearm assaults on roadways in 1985 followed by 
91 in 1986 and 137 in 1987 said the researchers who used figures 
compiled by california law enforcement agencies assaults were 
defined as shootings or the threatening display of a gun 
california authorities were unable to provide 1988 figures 
thursday but california highway patrol officer jill angel said the 
number of highway shootings had dropped dramatically since 1987 
our last confirmed shooting was in july 1988 she said 
highway violence is still going on in terms of fights between 
drivers angel added we average anywhere between five and 10 
incidents a week we just arent getting the reported shootings 
of the 137 assaults in 1987 83 or 61 percent were actual 
shootings the study said in the other 54 cases a gun was 
displayed but not fired the breakdown for other years was not 
provided 
two of the 1987 shootings were fatal and 15 caused wounds said 
the authors who had been asked by california health officials to 
look into highway shootings 
the assaults occurred on all types of roads but usually took 
place on surface streets defined as streets with speed limits of 
35 mph or less said onwuachisaunders 
of the 1987 cases only 49 or 36 percent occurred on freeways 
and one incident occurred on a highway the researchers said 
unlike freeways highways have intersections and traffic lights 
in 38 percent of the incidents victims told police some sort of 
interaction with the gunman had occurred such as changing lanes 
the study said but in 45 percent no such provocation had taken 
place seventeen percent were unsure whether a drivingassociated 
act had prompted the attack 
onwuachisaunders said the chances of being assaulted by someone 
carrying a gun while driving are tinythe overall number of 
roadway assaults was very small she said 
