<TEXT>
a tanker carrying more than 14 million 
gallons of north slope crude oil remained in limbo thursday after 
state officials refused to let the vessel dock without a 
stateapproved oil spill contingency plan 
the unocal corp vessel the sansinena ii was bound for the 
tesoroalaska petroleum co refinery with 147 million gallons of 
oil when the state department of environmental conservation denied 
it permission to dock on tuesday 
dec commissioner dennis kelso said the agency had checked the 
schedule of incoming tanker traffic and noticed the tanker had no 
stateapproved spill plan 
were still continuing to work on the problem said barry 
lane a unocal spokesman in los angeles we do know we do have a 
plan for the vessel we thought we had a stateapproved plan were 
in the process of updating it 
cook inlet and prince william sound have been the focus of 
heightened dec review since the march 24 grounding of the tanker 
exxon valdez the 11 million gallon spill coated 1000 miles of 
shoreline from the sound to cook inlet disrupting fishing seasons 
after the grounding the dec announced that cook inlet tanker 
traffic would be reexamined the department said it would turn 
away tankers lacking appropriate spill contingency plans 
kelso however said the unocal tanker was nabbed under a law 
strengthened last year after the tanker glacier bay in july 1987 
spilled 125000 gallons of oil into the inlets salmonrich waters 
the law requires spill contingency plans for any vessel carrying 
more than 420000 gallons of oil and allows the dec to ensure they 
will work 
the 810foot unocal tanker with a capacity of slightly more 
than 22 million gallons has been sailing between alaska and san 
francisco since it was built in 1971 lane said 
larry dietrick the decs environmental quality director said 
unocal had asked for and been denied a variance that would allow 
the tanker to load or unload in cook inlet 
the sansinena ii is the third tanker caught this year operating 
in cook inlet waters without a spill plan kelso said 
unocal had planned for the vessel to unload its cargo at the 
refinery in nikiski a small port community on the kenai peninsula 
the ship was then supposed to pick up cook inlet crude oil before 
returning to california said joe sautner an environmental field 
officer in the decs oil program 
unocal submitted a plan for the tanker late wednesday and it 
was under review thursday kelso said state officials have up to 
65 days to review such plans but they said it seldom takes that 
long 
while unocal made reference to plans submitted in 1978 and 1984 
those could not be found and would have expired in three years 
sautner said 
sautner said the new unocal plan would be reviewed carefully 
but he added that state officials were anxious to find some way of 
allowing the tanker to unload to reduce the chances of an incident 
we are suggesting they unocal officials first look into 
whether they can contract with another company that has an approved 
plan so they might be covered that way dec spokesman joe 
ferguson 
unocal has other vessels but not working in cook inlet and 
carrying the necessary plan sautner said 
if another company amended its plan to incorporate the tanker 
the vessel would be treated as that companys in the event of a 
spill and that might make it difficult to find a willing company 
he said 
</TEXT>
