broadcast and cable industry executives appear 
close to ending their bitter fight over who gets the best channel 
positions on viewers televisions 
the executives indicated at a senate hearing that they intended 
to stop their feud over what channels broadcast stations should get 
on cable tv systems and give the federal communications commission 
a chance to adopt procedures to arbitrate such disputes 
such a ceasefire which was proposed wednesday by sen daniel 
inouye dhawaii at a hearing of the senate commerce 
communications subcommittee inouye chairs would clear the way for 
a broadcastcable agreement on new rules to determine which 
stations cable systems must carry 
the fcc had established must carry rules in 1965 that had 
required cable systems to carry all or most local broadcast 
signals and mostly on their fccdesignated channels but a court 
struck down the rules in 1985 on constitutional freespeech 
grounds 
broadcasters have claimed that without the rules cable systems 
have been dropping local stations or changing the channel positions 
assigned by the fcc 
inouyes subcommittee has been working with the tv industry to 
write new rules that will pass court scrutiny but the 
channelpositioning controversy has held up agreement 
james mooney president of the national cable television 
association told inouye on wednesday he was amenable to inouyes 
plan national association of broadcasters president edward o 
fritts said he would be glad to present the proposal to his board 
of directors as did preston padden president of the association 
of independent television stations 
inouye said he believed mustcarry legislation could be passed 
before the end of this year perhaps by attaching it to pending 
legislation that would reimpose commercial advertising limits on 
childrens television shows 
broadcasters claim they are disadvantaged when a cable system 
bumps them from their overtheair channel positions often the 
broadcasters get pushed to higher numbers on the tv dial which 
broadcasters call cable siberia and away from the mostwatched 
213 channel positions some cableconnected tvs dont receive 
channels higher than 13 
the fccs mustcarry rules required cable systems to carry all 
or most of the local broadcast signals in their service area and 
vhf stations 213 on channel 
after the 1985 ruling the fcc adopted new mustcarry rules 
without any onchannel requirement but the court struck those down 
in 1987 finding that the fcc had not justified the requirements 
