<TEXT>
a us proposal to reform world agricultural trade 
by phasing out farm supports export subsidies and import tariffs 
received a mixed reaction from negotiators at the 97nation general 
agreement on tariffs and trade 
a trade source said wednesday the european community and japan 
criticized the proposal as being too drastic while countries such 
as canada and australia which do not subsidize agriculture welcomed 
the document 
third world nations relying on imports of farm produce voiced 
concern that the plan might increase the price of these imports he 
added 
deputy us trade representative julius katz described the 
proposal as realistic and said it was essential to extend 
gatts freetrade principles to agriculture 
the plan unveiled in washington on tuesday calls for the 
abolition of export subsidies within five years and the phasing out 
of national farm support measures that distort trade within 10 
years 
it also says import barriers such as quotas should be converted 
into tariffs and these should gradually be reduced over a 10year 
period 
the us proposal to reform world farm trade is the most 
comprehensive to be put on the table so far in the gattsponsored 
uruguay round of trade negotiations which close at the end of 1990 
however ec negotiator rolf moehler told the meeting in geneva 
that the proposal risked stopping the clock on agricultural 
negotiations the trade source said 
moehler said the ec was in favor of gradual but not overnight 
reform 
officials in brussels said the proposal would destroy the ecs 
agricultural policy and said it did not form an adequate basis 
for negotiation 
they accused the united states of disregarding an april 
agreement that called for progressive and substantial reductions in 
farm supports but not for total elimination 
more than half the ecs annual budget is spent on supporting 
farmers through the common agricultural policy 
the united states has said that the cost of farm programs to the 
industrial countries alone amounts to 165 billion a year 130 
billion of which is borne by consumers and taxpayers 
the fouryear uruguay round is also trying to agree on new trade 
rules on areas such as textiles tropical products copyright and 
other intellectual property rights and services like tourism and 
transportation 
