they saw no reason why top thrift regulator m danny wall rejected 
their 1987 recommendation 
the committee conducted the second of four scheduled hearings 
into the failure of lincoln based in irvine calif which is 
expected to cost taxpayers 2 billion making it the nations 
costliest thrift collapse 
patriarca and black said they tried to have lincoln closed to 
stop its losses but were thwarted by the vigorous lobbying of its 
owner phoenix millionaire charles h keating jr 
the government did not take over lincoln until this april 
allowing the institution to pile up millions in additional losses 
the panel is focusing on a decision by wall director of the 
thrift office to take patriarca and black off the case and 
transfer it to washingtonbased examiners who subsequently 
recommended against a government takeover 
i was astonished that the washington regulators would 
recommend against a receivership frankly i still find that 
astonishing patriarca said 
clearly we were shot in the back by the washington 
regulators when we battled to protect the taxpayers from lincoln 
savings black said 
rep henry b gonzalez dtexas chairman of the banking panel 
said of wall the chief federal regulator in washington dc 
willingly cut the legs out from under his regulatory troops in 
the middle of the battle 
patriarca told the committee keating wielded influence in all 
three branches of government 
when it came to influence the keating crowd really outshone 
the texas crowd he said in a reference to notorious sampl fraud 
cases in that state 
black said a 1985 letter from federal reserve board chairman 
alan greenspan then a private economist saying lincoln was a 
strong institution was particularly influential with members of 
congress 
gonzalez earlier had accused wall of trying to influence todays 
testimony by summoning patriarca and black to a meeting with a 
thrift agency attorney in washington on oct 10 
however karl hoyle a spokesman for wall said the oct 10 
meeting was voluntary and was called to minimize misconceptions 
rather than to influence the two 
nobodys telling them what to say theyll be under oath 
hoyle said the object was to give the committee the full story 
in another development a source in the office of thrift 
supervision who spoke on condition of anonymity said justice 
department investigators questioned thrift office officials about 
allegations that keating padded top employees salaries with the 
understanding they would contribute to political campaigns 
the los angeles daily news reported over the weekend that the 
thrift office and the federal deposit insurance corp referred the 
matter to the fbi for a criminal investigation after they found 
evidence that political contributions from lincoln were laundered 
through employee salaries 
spokesmen for the thrift office and the fdic would not say 
whether regulators made the referral an fbi spokesman said it is 
against the agencys policy to reveal the existence of an 
investigation 
a lawyer representing keating had no immediate comment 
