<TEXT>
nigel lawson resigned today as chancellor of the 
exchequer because of disagreements with an economic adviser to 
prime minister margaret thatcher the treasury said 
the resignation of britains top economic official was effective 
immediately 
lawson told mrs thatcher in a letter released by the treasury 
that he could not serve as her treasury secretary as long as she 
continued to take advice from sir alan walters her personal 
economic adviser 
lawson wrote i have therefore regretfully concluded that it 
is in the best interests of the government for me to resign my 
office without further ado 
lawson said he would continue to support the government as a 
member of parliament 
mrs thatcher quickly named foreign secretary john major as his 
replacement major is a former senior treasury official 
there have been persistent press reports that lawson suspected 
mrs thatcher was ignoring his advice and relying on walters 
instead 
the resignation was seen as a severe blow to her cabinet at a 
time of high inflation and interest rates and declining ratings in 
the opinion polls for her conservative party 
lawson and walters main difference was believed to have focused 
on britains attitude on the european monetary system 
lawson favored linking the pound to the exchange rate mechanism 
which limits swings in currencies but walters was openly against 
it 
lawson 57 became chancellor in 1983 
