<TEXT>
president bush citing valid concerns over 
food safety regulation because of stories of pesticidetainted 
apples and other foods today proposed legislation allowing 
pesticides to be taken off the market more quickly 
the plan attacked in advance by environmentalists as a step 
backward in some areas would overhaul pesticide regulation laws 
enforced by the environmental protection agency and the food and 
drug administration 
the president said the plan which he called a major 
initiative on food safety was partly in response to publics 
concern over stories alleging the presence of dangerous levels of 
pesticides 
bush said we have the safest food supply in the world im 
absolutely convinced of that and were going to keep it that way 
and while claiming the nations food supply to be safe he said 
some of the publics perception is based on valid concerns about 
the governments slow and cumbersome process for removing 
pesticides from the market 
bush commented during in a picturetaking session with 
administration officials involved in developing the package a task 
he said took several months 
the president mentioned a high degree of awareness by americans 
of news stories earlier this year on the presence of the 
cancercausing chemical alar on some apples and more recently 
concern about the widespread use of the fungicide ebdc on fruits 
and vegetables 
these stories have fueled the public concern about cancer 
risks and more important for us have called into question the 
governments ability to insure a safe supply of food for our 
citizens bush said 
earlier white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the plan 
would streamline epas ability to remove potentially hazardous 
pesticides from the market and enhance the agencys enforcement 
program 
he also said it would tighten fda rules governing the allowable 
tolerances of pesticide residues in food 
overall the plan is a comprehensive program to enhance food 
safety for all americans fitzwater said 
environmentalists began attacking the plan as information began 
surfacing on wednesday 
from our side its worse than the current law said janet 
hathaway a lawyer for the natural resources defense council which 
has been a sharp critic of the governments control of pesticides 
on food products 
responding to the criticism fitzwater said environmentalists 
were being appropriately wary as they always are in these 
cases 
he conceded that one aspect of the plan would require states to 
obtain special waivers to enact tougher foodsafety standards 
than the federal government 
currently no such waivers are required 
still fitzwater said a major benefit of the plan would be in 
giving the government the ability to take suspect pesticides off 
the market swiftly 
currently a long process that sometimes takes months and 
years to do is required he said 
these changes are designed to speed that up make it easier to 
stop the production or the use of pesticides while government 
regulators are considering a total ban the spokesman said 
the pesticide issue gained widespread attention earlier this 
year during the public outcry over use of alar on apples the epa 
acknowledged that alar caused cancer but said it could not be taken 
off the market immediately the manufacturer later stopped selling 
the chemical voluntarily 
while epa administrator william k reilly declined to discuss 
details of the proposal pending the white house announcement he 
said it was responsive to a number of problems this agency has 
had in administering our pesticide law 
sources familiar with the administration plan said it calls for 
a shift in the way the epa determines whether a potentially 
dangerous chemical used on food may be taken off the market 
relying on less timeconsuming rulemaking procedures instead of 
lengthy judicial hearings 
it also gives the epa greater leeway to suspend use of a 
chemical without first having to show an imminent hazard to 
public health as is now required sources said in some cases the 
agency will not have to consider economic costs in suspending use 
of a chemical if the health risks are considered substantial 
environmentalists praised such changes but criticized other 
provisions expected to be in the presidents plan 
ms hathaway said environmentalists are expected to oppose a 
provision calling on congress to establish uniform pesticide 
standards nationwide because that she said would effectively 
preempt stronger state laws 
in addition the presidents plan was expected to call for 
relaxing the threshold at which a chemical will be considered to 
pose an unacceptable health risk the epa has been using a risk 
level of 1 in 1 million as the benchmark that triggers regulatory 
action under the presidents plan the threshold in some cases 
could be increased to 1 in 100000 
were talking about an erosion of the concept of negligible 
risk here said ms hathaway arguing that a risk level of 1 in 
100000 is not adequate to protect the public 
</TEXT>
