<TEXT>
mcdonalds corp announced thursday its 
restaurants in new england would join forces with a consortium of 
chemical companies to launch a major recycling effort for plastic 
food containers 
mcdonalds is undertaking the program with the national 
polystyrene recycling co a joint venture formed earlier this year 
by several leading producers of plastics including amoco chemical 
co dow chemical co and arco chemical co 
polystyrene products which are not biodegradable have received 
criticism around the country as more than a dozen cities have 
enacted bans on the plastic products 
but officials who spoke at a news conference at a downtown 
mcdonalds said garbage problems cannot be solved simply by 
switching to more biodegradable materials 
where we have a shortage of space in landfills the solution 
lies in putting in less said shelby yastrow mcdonalds senior 
vice president 
ken harman acting chairman of the nprc and director of styrene 
products for dow said landfills inhibit all products from 
biodegrading so to put paper in instead of plastic you dont 
really accomplish anything 
the recycling company has set a goal to recycle 250 million 
pounds of polystyrene per year by 1995 an amount equal to 25 
percent of the polystyrene produced in the united states for food 
service and packaging each year 
harman said new england is serving as the launch site for the 
program because the company has acquired plastics again a 
recycling plant in leominster 
here were ready he said we have a plant we have a 
capability 
the company said it plans to establish four other regional 
recycling centers by the end of 1990 these centers are planned for 
chicago philadelphia southern california and the san francisco 
area 
under the program with mcdonalds restaurant customers will be 
asked to place their polystyrene foam containers utensils salad 
containers hot drink and sundae cups in special trash bins marked 
for recyclable plastic only 
after the recyclable material is taken to the leominster plant 
it will be turned into plastic resins which then will be sold to 
companies that manufacture plastic products 
customers are already being asked to separate their plastic 
waste at 100 mcdonalds restaurants in new england yastrow said 
and about 450 restaurants are expected to be participating by early 
next year 
based on initial tests mcdonalds expects 70 percent of its 
polystyrene waste products will be turned in for recycling yastrow 
said 
richard denison a senior scientist with the environmental 
defense fund said he was encouraged by mcdonalds efforts 
providing customers with an ability to recycle in their stores 
is an important first step denison said in an interview from 
washington dc 
but denison said the program also could have limitations 
it only affects customers who eat in he said people who 
take materials out of the store would have to be awfully ambitious 
to participate in this 
mcdonalds officials estimate that at restaurants equipped with 
drivein windows 40 percent to 50 percent of its customers use 
that service 
but yastrow expressed hope that people who take their food away 
from the restaurants will separate their plastic items once they 
learn about the effort 
in fact officials said educating customers about recycling was 
a key part of the program 
we need to have more initiatives like the one were seeing 
today said paul keough acting regional administrator for the 
us environmental protection agency i hope that its wildly 
successful and will be copied around the country 
tom tomaszek general manager of plastics again in leominster 
noted that next month sturbridge is scheduled to start what is 
believed to be the first community program for separating 
polystyrene products 
</TEXT>
