<TEXT>
privatesector workers who got new contracts 
through collective bargaining from january through september won 
average annual wage increases of 31 percent compared to average 
gains of 24 percent in their prior contracts the labor department 
said thursday 
the data covers contracts for 13 million workers negotiated in 
the first nine months of the year if the trend continues for the 
final three months 1989 would be the first year since 1981 in 
which new contracts provide workers with better pay raises on 
average than their prior contracts the department said 
the rebound in wage gains was attributed to the restoration of 
prior concessions in several industries that were slumping earlier 
in the decade particularly the us steel industry 
also the labor department said wage increases given to workers 
in the health care sector particularly nurses were outpacing the 
gains provided in prior contracts competition for skilled workers 
in that sector has pushed wages higher 
the departments bureau of labor statistics tracks collective 
bargaining agreements affecting 6 million workers in bargaining 
units of at least 1000 employees 
contracts affecting an additional 903000 workers in the private 
sector are up for collective bargaining in the fourth quarter more 
than onethird of those workers are rail workers the government 
said 
most of the settlements reached in the first nine months of the 
year 81 percent covering 1 million of the 13 million workers 
were in nonmanufacturing sectors about onethird of those were in 
the construction industry where settlements called for average 
annual wage increases of 30 percent the settlements in the other 
nonmanufacturing sectors primarily communications food stores 
and utilities provided average annual pay hikes of 33 percent 
the government said 
in manufacturing a sector which has slumped most of the year 
the settlements provided lower wage adjustments averaging 29 
percent a year over the life of the new contracts 
