<TEXT>
by barry massey 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
congress passed and sent legislation to 
president bush on thursday to give a break to farmers who are 
growing substitute crops on land where drought destroyed or damaged 
earlier plantings 
the bill eases restrictions on a federal disaster aid package 
enacted earlier this year 
it is intended to protect winter wheat and cotton farmers who 
might receive no disaster payments for their lost crops under an 
agriculture department plan even though the producers expect to 
earn little or no profit on replacement crops such as grain sorghum 
or soybeans 
the legislation was approved wednesday by the senate and passed 
the house on a voice vote thursday with technical amendments it 
returned to the senate later in the day and was approved easily 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said he was confident 
that bush would sign the legislation 
the agriculture department trying to prevent farmers from 
reaping double benefits has been planning to deduct 75 percent of 
the gross value of any replacement crop from the disaster payment a 
farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop 
under the bill that system would be modified 
farmers would have no payment deductions if the replacement 
crops failed to produce more than 50 percent of the county average 
yield for the second crop 
but if the yield exceeded 50 percent of average yield the 
agriculture departments formula for deductions would kick in and 
be applied only to the portion of the crop that exceeded the 50 
percent mark 
under the agriculture departments initial plan even farmers 
who had replanted only a few acres would have to wait until 
harvesting their second crop before obtaining disaster benefits for 
damage to the first crop 
that provision would be canceled under the legislation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

